## Building a Search Bar with History in React

**Mental model:** On submit, push the query onto a recent-searches list — most-recent-first, de-duplicated, capped to N. A dropdown shows the history when the input is focused; clicking an item re-runs it. (In a real app the list persists to `localStorage`.)

### Step 1 — Query + history
```jsx
const [query, setQuery] = useState('');
const [history, setHistory] = useState([]);
```

### Step 2 — Add on submit (dedupe + cap + recency)
Remove any existing copy, unshift to front, slice to the cap.

```jsx
const submit = (q) => {
  const t = q.trim();
  if (!t) return;
  setHistory((h) => [t, ...h.filter((x) => x !== t)].slice(0, MAX));
};
```

### Step 3 — Show history on focus
```jsx
{focused && history.length > 0 && (
  <ul>{history.map((h) => <li onMouseDown={() => reuse(h)}>{h}</li>)}</ul>
)}
```

### Step 4 — Reuse + clear
```jsx
const reuse = (q) => { setQuery(q); submit(q); };
const clear = () => setHistory([]);
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Duplicate search | Filter out old copy, re-add at front. |
| History overflow | `slice(0, MAX)`. |
| Click vs blur | `onMouseDown` fires before the input's blur. |

**Interview tip:** The `[t, ...h.filter(x => x !== t)].slice(0, MAX)` one-liner captures dedupe + recency + cap together — and mention `localStorage` (with a lazy initializer) for persistence across reloads.

